## Ship It

```bash
git add src/components/ui/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpy.tsx \
        src/components/ui/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpy.module.scss
git commit -m "fix(ScrollSpy): resolve portaled active label X offset in JS, not CSS

The anchor's CSS transform: translate(calc(-100% - spacer), -50%) relied on
-100% resolving against the anchor's own rendered width. But will-change:
top, left promotes the element to a GPU layer before child text renders,
collapsing -100% to 0 — the label landed to the right of the notch and
clipped past the viewport on long titles.

Fix: compute left = notch.left - anchorRef.offsetWidth - SPACER_1X in JS
(matching .label's right: calc(100% + spacer-1x) gutter exactly). CSS
transform retains only translateY(-50%) whose -50% resolves against the
known line-height box, not a 0-width ghost. Added ResizeObserver on the
anchor so first-hover zero-width frames self-correct on next paint.

Removed will-change: top, left from .highlightLabelAnchor — the GPU hint
that triggered early promotion is no longer needed (left is baked in JS;
the transform is now a single-axis Y-only value). will-change: transform,
opacity on .highlightLabel (the motion.span) is retained.

Refs: AP-070, FB-156"
```

---

## Principle

**AP-070** — *framer-motion `x`/`y`/`scale`/`rotate` on an element with a base CSS `transform`.* This was the guiding anti-pattern for the two-element split. The current bug is its sibling: **`will-change` on a positioned element makes CSS `transform` percentages unreliable** because GPU layer promotion happens before the element's natural layout width is established. The rule generalizes: **never use `transform: translate(-N%, …)` to position a portaled element whose width is unknown at layer-promotion time.** If you need to right-align a dynamically-sized label, either (a) resolve the offset in JS against a ref'd `offsetWidth`, or (b) use `right: 0` with an RTL text-flow trick — never rely on `-100%` when `will-change` is in play.
